metadata.name: Retroscapes #212
metadata.description:
You are approaching newly discovered planetary ring system, seen by no human before.
Gravity works in strange ways there. Intrigued, you grab your polaroid. 
Snap, and there it is - your grainy Retroscape.

Beauty comes from diversity.

Size of the collection - 222 pieces - is a tribute to my first NFT.

metadata.name: Permutation City #158
metadata.description:
The work is inspired by the novel Permutation City by Greg Egan, the author of the hard science fiction.

It raises the issue of whether we can in principle understand that we exist in reality or in a simulation.

According to the Theory of Dust (which is described in the novel), the universe is simulatable and all other possible universes are equally as real as ours, emerging spontaneously from their own mathematical self-consistency. Human consciousness is¬†Turing-computable, which means that consciousness can be also produced by a computer program.

The¬†Autoverse¬†is an¬†artificial life¬†simulator, a massive complex cellular automaton universe, producing cities and the consciousness of human copies.

Gradually, due to failures and a lack of computing power, the idea of the reliability of such universes is destroyed. 

Spaces crumble, cities become fluid and drain down, turning into dust and digital glitch.

Thanks to Yulikolay for helping with code, using p5.Riso.js library for generating files suitable for risograph printing.
Source images for permutation cities are made with a help of DALL¬∑E mini neural network.

metadata.name: Omega Point #175
metadata.description:
In the collapsing universe approaching singularity, the last remaining cybernetic organisms encounter the state of infinite knowledge, information, and computational resources.
Although the living creatures in the Omega Point are destined for imminent destruction, they experience infinite life.

----

Live mode controls:
'r' - change resolution
's' - save PNG
'space' - improve image quality
'f' - increase rendering speed

The image quality gradually improves over time, up to a certain level. To reach the maximum quality, press 'space'.
The rendering speed is reduced by default - press 'f' for the maximum speed.

Rendering may be GPU intensive.
Requires WebGL2.

metadata.name: Orchard #156
metadata.description:
A natural media rendering of a fruit tree during one of the four seasons. Sometimes, you'll catch it at night - with lights strung on the tree!

The amount of color in spring and fall, snow in winter, fruit on and off the tree will all vary. There are four spring bloom palettes, four trunk colors, and seven types of fruit. 

Press ‚Äôs‚Äô to save a screenshot. Image size is 1000x1000px
Press ‚Äôp‚Äô to pause/resume.

To render a variation at a new size, open live view and append '?size=#' to the end of the URL. The new size may be from 100 to 3,000. This version will not be a 1:1 match to your edition but will have all of the same features.

metadata.name: A Slight Case of Overbombing #38
metadata.description:
Inspired by monochromatic art of the late 60s, Russian folk-art woodblock prints, and the stylised colours of British underground comics, excited to introduce a series of bold rich landscapes. England, Wales, Ireland and Scotland represented by red, yellow, green and blue, sometimes a house or two, and groovy clouds.

Instructions ::

.     - speed up
,     - slow down
space - pause
n     - toggle noise
p     - cycle palette
h     - toggle high-res (and definitely intentional pixel shift)
s     - download and save image
